\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The study of eukaryotic genomes has revealed a variety of proteins which
 bind to the DNA to control and regulate gene expression.
 Transcription factors are a type of DNA-binding protein that are important
 for regulating gene expression.
 Most transcription factors tend to bind to a specific DNA sequences, and
 finding these transcription factor binding sites has been important for
 understanding gene regulation.
 The regulatory functions of DNA-binding proteins have been understood in
 different ways, but an important methodology to experimentally profile
 DNA protein interactions is chromatin immunoprecipitation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-ChIP-seq-workflow"

\end_inset

).
 Chromatin immunoprecipitation uses specific antibodies to “grab” a particular
 protein and the DNA it is attached to, and by using high throughput sequencing
 methods, these short DNA fragments can be sequenced.
 Chromatin immunoprecipitation combined with high-throughput sequencing
 (ChIP-seq) provides a whole-genome view of the DNA-protein binding sites.
 New computational tasks have become important for analyzing ChIP-seq in
 order to identify these binding sites, and to compare the binding sites
 across different experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using ChIP-seq data, transcription factor binding sites can be identified
 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peaks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the number of reads that cover a particular genome position.
 There have been many improvements to these 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peak finding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algorithms, but most of these algorithms have been developed to find transcript
ion factor binding sites from individual experiments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wilbanks_evaluation_2010"

\end_inset

.
 One approach for comparing the binding sites from different experiments
 is to analyze experiments individually and then comparing the overlap of
 the nearest gene for each the binding sites (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Illustration-of-gene-centric"

\end_inset

).
 Another method is to compare the overlap of the binding site positions
 in each experiment by using syntenic or aligned genome coordinates.
 
\end_layout

