 yeast strains using a normalization called NormDiff.
 NormDiff uses background subtraction and normalization and the significant
 differences across experiments are identified as variable binding regions,
 which are defined as regions where the variance of NormDiff scores is across
 all experiments is high.
 The variable binding regions are used to characterize the binding differences
 in the yeast ChIP-seq, and over 80% of the variable binding regions overlap
 significant binding sites identified using peak calling with MACS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
