 are extracted from a cell lysate.
 Afterwards, the proteins are unlinked from the DNA resulting in a DNA library
 that is enriched for the DNA-binding sites.
 Transcription factors have been extensively studied using chromatin immunopreci
pitation (ChIP) which effectively creates a DNA library that is enriched
 for a particular DNA-binding protein of interest.
 Classic techniques for chromatin immunoprecipitation have used PCR based
 techniques, but new high-throughput sequencing combined has used with chromatin
 immunoprecipitation (ChIP-seq) to provide a whole-genome quantitative view
 transcription factor binding sites.
 Many different variations on the ChIP protocols and on the DNA sequence
 analysis have been developed 
