\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison of ChIP experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compare the results of chromatin immunoprecipitation for transcription
 factor binding sites, a general assessment of whether the binding sites
 are the same or different look at the overlapping peaks (peak-centric approach)
 or the overlapping target-genes (gene-centric approach).
 Both the gene-centric and peak-centric approaches were evaluated by
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

 for comparing transcription factor binding sites between mouse and human
 liver tissues.
 They showed that a large percentage of all binding sites, between 41-80%,
 are not conserved across speces.
 Even sequences that are aligned and have conserved sequence motifs do not
 strongly predict conserved binding events, and only about 1/3 of the binding
 events have a sequence alignment from human to mouse 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The microarray technology that uses printed oligonucleotides to study mRNA
 sequencing was one the gene-centric approach was important because the
 microarrays were printed with oligonucleotides corresponding to genes.
 This enabled microarray gene expression experiments to detect mRNA expression
 levels, and so a gene to gene comparison was a clear discriminator.
 Using chromatin immunoprecipitation microarrays (ChIP-chip) the microarrays
 would be printed with oligonucleotides upstream of the target genes in
 order to detect the transcription factors that are the most likely regulators.
 The peak-centric approach was first started using high-density oligonucleotide
 arrays 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "odom_tissue-specific_2007"

\end_inset

 which gives higher resolution and therefore allows detection of narrower
 transcription factor binding site peaks.
 Using the peak-centric approach, overlapping peaks can be detected directly,
 and the target gene is not necessarily inferred, which has advantages for
 comparing the sequence similarity.
 Nevertheless, both approaches have advantages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finding transcription factor binding sites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We looked at a popular and open-source software package for peak finding
 -- MACS (Model-based analysis of ChIP-seq).
 Brief overview of the peak calling methodology is as follows: To find the
 potential binding sites from the data, MACS calculates the distribution
 of reads in the background that are not associated with any transcription
 factor binding.
 MACS uses a Poisson distribution to model the expected number of in the
 scanning window given the total number of reads and the whole genome size.
 Then peaks are identified as the likelihood of receiving a large number
 of reads in our scan window compared with the background.
 The resulting output is a list of high confidence ChIP-seq peaks that represent
 potential transcription factor binding sites.
 The statistical problem of peak finding is a classic problem: they must
 be discriminate enough to avoid false positives, but they must also be
 sensitive enough to avoid false negatives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, the read depth of a peak can be highly dependant on the library
 size of the sequenced reads, and sampling the data to impose the same library
 size would discard large proportions of the data in some cases.
 If p-values that represent the significant differences relative to a background
, however the background can be highly variable depending on the enrichment
 of the ChIP protocol.
 A false discovery rate (FDR) can be calculated for each peak 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zhang_model-based_2008"

\end_inset

, but the technique used implicitely ranks the peaks by p-value.
 These shortcomings have led to some alternative approaches for comparing
 binding sites from different ChIP-seq experiments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MACS has been shown to have wide popularity and it shows a good ability
 to identify peaks, but the methods that have been offered for comparing
 experiments using MACS have been limited.a
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identifying differential binding sites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been a variety of methods for finding differential binding sites
 from ChIP-seq data.
 As we have shown previously in the gene-centric or peak-centric approach,
 then differential binding sites are represented by non-overlapping binding
 sites or non-overlapping target genes after these features are identified
 in each individual experiment.
 However, this method does not give provide a sense of differential quantificati
on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach for doing a differential analysis using a typical peak finder
 such as MACS is to use one ChIP-seq experiment as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

false control
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 data and then supply the another as the normal ChIP-seq.
 Then, differences in the peaks are found when large differences from the
 one experiment exceeds the false control.
 If the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

false control
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 read count is low (not a peak in the control) and the read count is high
 in the compared set then it will be identified as differential.
 This method has some intuitive advantages, however, it does not satisfy
 some problems.
 Firstly it does not necessarily incorporate replicate data into it's findings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To incorporate replicates into a differential expression workflow, reads
 from the replicate experiments can be pooled simply by concatenating the
 read files.
 Pooling replicate experiments will increase the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saturation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and total sequencing depth however it is not very helpful for comparative
 and differential analysis.
 The differential expression problem for is called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small n, large p
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem for high-throughput experiments because there are few samples but
 and a lot of hypothesis tests about which sites are significantly different
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit_statistics_2004"

\end_inset

.
 Pooling reads to analyze differential expression is unusual from an experimenta
l design because it reduces our ability to analyze the variance across the
 samples.
 Replicates have been shown to be important in measuring differential expression
 in microarray data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wit_statistics_2004"

\end_inset

, and so we considered methods that are similar that would help us find
 differential peaks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A method for comparing ChIP-seq experiments directly using log-ratios is
 DIME.
 DIME uses a LOESS (locally weighted scatterplot smoothing) normalization
 which has been applied to other normalizations such as DIME 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taslim_comparative_2009"

\end_inset

.
 Differential peaks according to maximum likelihood expectation from a mixture
 model of K-Normal and Exponential (GNG) or NUDGE (Normal-Uniform).
 Finally there is the NormDiff method for finding highly variable binding
 regions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zheng_genetic_2010"

\end_inset

.
